3:02 correction. a map is just a piece of paper only if you're using a cartography table. If you don't have a cartography table, a map is nine sheets of paper. For a locator map, it's eight paper + 1 redstone + 4 iron ingots.
If you want a map that's more than level 0 zoom, you have to add more paper. One sheet for each zoom out if you're using a cartography table, eight sheets for each zoom out if you're using a crafting table.
To know how much paper the cartographer's maps are worth you'd have to take account of what zoom level they are, and whether you already have access to a cartography table or want to make a new one.

snippet.textDisplay: You guys missed the fact that Steve is a super human, but villagers are not. Therefore, if an emerald did weigh around 600 lbs. Then how would trading one emerald to a villager make any sense, that is way to heavy for the villager to carry. So the second theory Matt had about the emeralds costing around $60 makes the most sense. For a bundle of sticks and some carrots, $60 is already overpriced but since it's the villagers labor then it's completely logical to them. Also since they don't live in our society emeralds are going to cost less, since survival tools and food is way more important to them then a flat screen tv, or a nice house.

snippet.textDisplay:
To try and put a tangible amount of worth on Minecraft emeralds is basically impossible. Which is why I’m glad MatPat explained this. Money only has a value based on subjective views, which is why say 1 diamond can be worth 1 emerald and 22 carrots is also worth 1 emerald. Money is only a medium, otherwise we would trade 22 carrots for 1 diamond. Money just makes trade simpler than trading carrots for diamonds.
That’s why bottle caps are used in fallout (along with NCR dollars and Legion coins), they’re agreed upon currency that have 0 objective value but are backed by the subjective value of water (see fallout 1’s Hub Water Merchants). It’s also why the NCR dollar lost value, it’s perceived worth was lost and went back to the caps system. That’s because water will always have value in the wasteland, but it’s easier to trade caps for a gun than gallons of purified water.
Emeralds in Minecraft will only have value if the Villagers see it as valuable. So unless they all decide emeralds aren’t good for anything, you’d just trade 22 carrots for 1 diamond. Money is worthless by itself, but a society that agrees upon its use, being equal to a worthy object like water, will give it value.
